  <div class="checklist-disclaimer">
    <p><strong>NON-CONTRACTUAL GUIDANCE</strong></p>
    <p>This checklist is provided as guidance only and does not form part of the tenancy agreement. It summarises key legal obligations for landlords in Scotland. For detailed requirements, consult the relevant legislation or seek professional legal advice.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>1. Landlord Registration (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Registered with the Scottish Landlord Register</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">All private landlords in Scotland must be registered with their local authority before letting a property. Registration numbers should be quoted in property advertisements.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Property included in registration</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Each property you let must be included in your landlord registration. Registration renewal is required every 3 years.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Antisocial Behaviour etc. (Scotland) Act 2004, Part 8</p>

  <h3>2. Private Residential Tenancy Agreement</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Written tenancy agreement provided</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">You must provide the tenant with a written tenancy agreement that includes all the statutory terms prescribed by the Scottish Government. The Model Tenancy Agreement can be used.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Easy Read Notes provided</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">You should provide the tenant with the Scottish Government's Easy Read Notes explaining their rights and responsibilities.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Private Housing (Tenancies) (Scotland) Act 2016, s.10</p>

  <h3>3. Deposit Protection (Mandatory)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Deposit protected within 30 working days</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">If you take a deposit, it must be protected in an approved tenancy deposit scheme within 30 working days of receipt. Scotland has approved schemes: SafeDeposits Scotland, Letting Protection Service Scotland, and mydeposits Scotland.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Deposit information provided</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">You must provide the tenant with information about which scheme holds their deposit, the deposit amount, and how the scheme's dispute resolution service works.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Tenancy Deposit Schemes (Scotland) Regulations 2011</p>

  <h3>4. Gas Safety (Mandatory if gas supplied)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Valid Gas Safety Certificate (CP12)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A Gas Safe registered engineer must inspect all gas appliances annually. The certificate must be provided before the tenant moves in.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Copy provided before occupation</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">New tenants must receive a copy before moving in. Keep proof of provision.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Gas Safety (Installation and Use) Regulations 1998</p>

  <h3>5. Energy Performance Certificate (EPC)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Valid EPC available</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">An EPC must be available for prospective tenants and provided to the tenant. Scotland is introducing minimum energy efficiency standards progressively.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>EPC rating displayed in adverts</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">The EPC rating must be included in property advertisements.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Energy Performance of Buildings (Scotland) Regulations 2008</p>

  <h3>6. Electrical Safety (EICR)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Electrical Installation Condition Report (EICR)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">While not currently a standalone legal requirement in Scotland, electrical installations must be safe under the Repairing Standard. Many landlords obtain 5-yearly EICRs as best practice.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Electrical safety confirmation to tenant</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Provide confirmation that electrical installations and appliances are safe.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing (Scotland) Act 2006 (Repairing Standard)</p>

  <h3>7. Repairing Standard</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Property meets the Repairing Standard</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">The property must meet the Repairing Standard from the start of the tenancy. This includes: wind and watertight structure, satisfactory provision for heating, hot and cold water, and sanitary facilities.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>All fixtures, fittings and appliances in reasonable repair</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Includes cooker, sink, basin, WC, bath/shower, fixed heating, and other provided appliances.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing (Scotland) Act 2006, ss.13-14</p>

  <h3>8. Smoke and Heat/CO Alarms</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Interlinked smoke alarms in living rooms and hallways</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Since 1 February 2022, all homes in Scotland must have interlinked fire alarms: smoke alarms in living rooms and hallways on each storey.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Heat alarms in kitchens</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A heat alarm must be installed in the kitchen (not a smoke alarm, as cooking triggers false alarms).</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Carbon monoxide detector where required</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">A CO detector is required in any room with a fixed combustion appliance (excluding gas cookers).</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing (Scotland) Act 2006 (Tolerable Standard) (Extension of Criteria) Order 2019</p>

  <h3>9. Legionella Risk Assessment</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>Legionella risk assessment completed</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Landlords should identify and assess sources of risk from Legionella in the water system. This is typically a simple visual check for most residential properties.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Health and Safety Executive Approved Code of Practice L8</p>

  <h3>10. HMO Requirements (If applicable)</h3>
  <table class="checklist-table">
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>HMO licence obtained (if required)</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Properties let to 3 or more unrelated people sharing facilities require an HMO licence from the local authority. This includes student flats.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td class="checkbox-cell">☐</td>
      <td>
        <strong>HMO licence conditions complied with</strong><br>
        <span class="guidance-text">Including fire safety equipment, maximum occupancy, and any specific conditions set by the council.</span>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="legal-ref">Housing (Scotland) Act 2006, Part 5</p>

